== Meiji Period: Shinbutsu Bunri and Haibutsu Kishaku == With the advent of the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新}}, government policies of {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離}} (separation of Buddhism and Shinto) and {{ill|Haibutsu kishaku|ja|廃仏毀釈}} (abolition of Buddhism) led to the suppression of Ochi Daigongen, as it was rooted in Shugendō traditions. The shrine-temple complex of Mount Ochi was forcibly divided, resulting in the establishment of {{ill|Ochi Shrine (Fukui)|ja|越知神社}} as an independent Shinto institution and the continued operation of the Buddhist temple, Ōtani-ji. Additionally, many stone Buddhist statues along the pilgrimage routes of Mount Ochi were destroyed as part of this religious restructuring.
