== Overview == In the second year of {{ill|Yōrō|ja|養老|12=draft}} (718 CE), the monk {{ill|Taichō|ja|泰澄|12=draft}} was engaged in ascetic training on Mount Ochi when he received divine inspiration from Ochi Daigongen.<ref>[http://www.moon.sphere.ne.jp/ochisan/den_ama.html Ochi-san Tourism Promotion Association - Legends of Taichō]</ref> This event marked the establishment of Mount Ochi as a Shugendō training ground. As an offshoot of {{ill|Hakusan Shugendō|ja|白山修験|12=draft}}, the faith and practice at Mount Ochi developed around {{ill|Ōtani-ji (Fukui)|ja|大谷寺 (福井県越前町)|12=draft}}, a temple founded by Taichō.<ref>[http://www.echizen-ohtanji.com/rekishi.htm Ōtani-ji - History]</ref> Within this structure, the main hall (hondō), inner sanctum (oku-no-in), and the "Separate Mountain" (Betsusan) housed the three principal deities of Ochi Daigongen: Eleven-faced Kannon, Amida Nyorai, and Shō Kannon.
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft}}, Ōtani-ji flourished due to its association as the prayer temple for {{ill|Yūki Hideyasu|ja|結城秀康|12=draft}}, the lord of the {{ill|Fukui Domain|ja|福井藩|12=draft}}. This patronage helped to expand the faith and practice surrounding Ochi Daigongen.
== Meiji Period: Shinbutsu Bunri and Haibutsu Kishaku == With the advent of the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft}}, government policies of {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}} (separation of Buddhism and Shinto) and {{ill|Haibutsu kishaku|ja|廃仏毀釈|12=draft}} (abolition of Buddhism) led to the suppression of Ochi Daigongen, as it was rooted in Shugendō traditions. The shrine-temple complex of Mount Ochi was forcibly divided, resulting in the establishment of {{ill|Ochi Shrine (Fukui)|ja|越知神社|12=draft}} as an independent Shinto institution and the continued operation of the Buddhist temple, Ōtani-ji. Additionally, many stone Buddhist statues along the pilgrimage routes of Mount Ochi were destroyed as part of this religious restructuring.
