'''Ochi Daigongen''' (越知大権現) is a syncretic deity combining [[:en:Mountain worship|mountain worship]] and [[:en:Shugendō|Shugendō]], particularly associated with {{ill|Mount Ochi|ja|越知山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Ochi|qq=}} in [[:en:Fukui Prefecture|Fukui Prefecture]], Japan. It is identified with the [[:en:Honji suijaku|Honji suijaku]] manifestation of [[:en:Ekādaśamukha|Eleven-faced Kannon]], [[:en:Amitābha|Amida Nyorai]], and {{ill|Shō Kannon|ja|聖観音|1=Āryāvalokiteśvara|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shō Kannon|13=User:Immanuelle/Āryāvalokiteśvara|qq=}}. It is also referred to as "Ochi-san Sansho Gongen" (越知山三所権現) or "Ochi-san Sansho Daigongen" (越知山三所大権現).

== Overview ==
In the second year of [[:en:Yōrō|Yōrō]] (718 CE), the monk [[:en:Taichō|Taichō]] was engaged in ascetic training on Mount Ochi when he received divine inspiration from Ochi Daigongen.<ref>[http://www.moon.sphere.ne.jp/ochisan/den_ama.html Ochi-san Tourism Promotion Association - Legends of Taichō]</ref> This event marked the establishment of Mount Ochi as a Shugendō training ground. As an offshoot of {{ill|Hakusan Shugendō|ja|白山修験|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakusan Shugendō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 白山信仰}}, the faith and practice at Mount Ochi developed around {{ill|Ōtani-ji (Fukui)|ja|大谷寺 (福井県越前町)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtani-ji (Fukui)|qq=}}, a temple founded by Taichō.<ref>[http://www.echizen-ohtanji.com/rekishi.htm Ōtani-ji - History]</ref> Within this structure, the main hall (hondō), inner sanctum (oku-no-in), and the "Separate Mountain" (Betsusan) housed the three principal deities of Ochi Daigongen: Eleven-faced Kannon, Amida Nyorai, and Shō Kannon.

During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], Ōtani-ji flourished due to its association as the prayer temple for [[:en:Yūki Hideyasu|Yūki Hideyasu]], the lord of the [[:en:Fukui Domain|Fukui Domain]]. This patronage helped to expand the faith and practice surrounding Ochi Daigongen.

== Meiji Period: Shinbutsu Bunri and Haibutsu Kishaku ==
With the advent of the [[:en:Meiji Restoration|Meiji Restoration]], government policies of [[:en:Shinbutsu bunri|Shinbutsu bunri]] (separation of Buddhism and Shinto) and [[:en:Haibutsu kishaku|Haibutsu kishaku]] (abolition of Buddhism) led to the suppression of Ochi Daigongen, as it was rooted in Shugendō traditions. The shrine-temple complex of Mount Ochi was forcibly divided, resulting in the establishment of {{ill|Ochi Shrine (Fukui)|ja|越知神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ochi Shrine (Fukui)|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} as an independent Shinto institution and the continued operation of the Buddhist temple, Ōtani-ji. Additionally, many stone Buddhist statues along the pilgrimage routes of Mount Ochi were destroyed as part of this religious restructuring.

