'''Ochi Daigongen''' (越知大権現) is a syncretic deity combining {{ill|Mountain worship|en|Mountain worship|WD=Q93697439|lt=mountain worship|1=Mountain worship}} and {{ill|Shugendō|en|Shugendō|WD=Q1483875|lt=Shugendō|1=Shugendō}}, particularly associated with {{ill|Mount Ochi|ja|越知山|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Ochi|1=Mount Ochi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q15259982}} in {{ill|Fukui Prefecture|en|Fukui Prefecture|WD=Q133879|lt=Fukui Prefecture|1=Fukui Prefecture}}, Japan. It is identified with the {{ill|Honji suijaku|en|Honji suijaku|WD=Q3080781|lt=Honji suijaku|1=Honji suijaku}} manifestation of {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|en|Ekādaśamukha|WD=Q11404731|lt=Eleven-faced Kannon|1=Ekādaśamukha}}, {{ill|Amitābha|en|Amitābha|WD=Q236242|lt=Amida Nyorai|1=Amitābha}}, and {{ill|Shō Kannon|ja|聖観音|1=Āryāvalokiteśvara|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shō Kannon|13=User:Immanuelle/Āryāvalokiteśvara|qq=}}. It is also referred to as "Ochi-san Sansho Gongen" (越知山三所権現) or "Ochi-san Sansho Daigongen" (越知山三所大権現).

== Overview ==
In the second year of {{ill|Yōrō|en|Yōrō|WD=Q1373061|lt=Yōrō|1=Yōrō}} (718 CE), the monk {{ill|Taichō|en|Taichō|WD=Q2388439|lt=Taichō|1=Taichō}} was engaged in ascetic training on Mount Ochi when he received divine inspiration from Ochi Daigongen.<ref>[http://www.moon.sphere.ne.jp/ochisan/den_ama.html Ochi-san Tourism Promotion Association - Legends of Taichō]</ref> This event marked the establishment of Mount Ochi as a Shugendō training ground. As an offshoot of {{ill|Hakusan Shugendō|ja|白山修験|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakusan Shugendō|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 白山信仰|1=Hakusan Faith|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11579557}}, the faith and practice at Mount Ochi developed around {{ill|Ōtani-ji (Fukui)|ja|大谷寺 (福井県越前町)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtani-ji (Fukui)|1=Otanji Temple|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11439052}}, a temple founded by Taichō.<ref>[http://www.echizen-ohtanji.com/rekishi.htm Ōtani-ji - History]</ref> Within this structure, the main hall (hondō), inner sanctum (oku-no-in), and the "Separate Mountain" (Betsusan) housed the three principal deities of Ochi Daigongen: Eleven-faced Kannon, Amida Nyorai, and Shō Kannon.

During the {{ill|Edo period|en|Edo period|WD=Q184963|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period}}, Ōtani-ji flourished due to its association as the prayer temple for {{ill|Yūki Hideyasu|en|Yūki Hideyasu|WD=Q1130929|lt=Yūki Hideyasu|1=Yūki Hideyasu}}, the lord of the {{ill|Fukui Domain|en|Fukui Domain|WD=Q903537|lt=Fukui Domain|1=Fukui Domain}}. This patronage helped to expand the faith and practice surrounding Ochi Daigongen.

== Meiji Period: Shinbutsu Bunri and Haibutsu Kishaku ==
With the advent of the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|en|Meiji Restoration|WD=Q8707|lt=Meiji Restoration|1=Meiji Restoration}}, government policies of {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|en|Shinbutsu bunri|WD=Q1970535|lt=Shinbutsu bunri|1=Shinbutsu bunri}} (separation of Buddhism and Shinto) and {{ill|Haibutsu kishaku|en|Haibutsu kishaku|WD=Q702298|lt=Haibutsu kishaku|1=Haibutsu kishaku}} (abolition of Buddhism) led to the suppression of Ochi Daigongen, as it was rooted in Shugendō traditions. The shrine-temple complex of Mount Ochi was forcibly divided, resulting in the establishment of {{ill|Ochi Shrine (Fukui)|ja|越知神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ochi Shrine (Fukui)|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} as an independent Shinto institution and the continued operation of the Buddhist temple, Ōtani-ji. Additionally, many stone Buddhist statues along the pilgrimage routes of Mount Ochi were destroyed as part of this religious restructuring.

